    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Mirrors made from polished obsidian, which is a dark, shiny glass formed in nature by the rapid cooling of lava. Such mirrors were used since Paleolithic times. In ancient Mesoamerica and elsewhere, they were often used as instruments for seeing.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000047822/MFA Conservation and Art Material Encyclopedia Online: CAMEO (2005-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079228/Grove Art Online (2008-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Spiegels gemaakt van gepolijst obsidiaan, een zwart, glanzend glas dat ontstaat wanneer lava snel afkoelt. Dergelijke spiegels werden sinds het paleolithicum gebruikt. In Midden-Amerika en andere regionen gebruikte men ze soms voor tovenarij.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>由拋光後的黑曜石所製作而成的鏡子；黑曜石是黑亮的玻璃，是在火山熔岩急速冷卻之後所天然形成的。這類鏡子自從舊石器時代起就為人們所使用。在古代的中美洲（Mesoamerica）和其他地方，黑曜石鏡子經常被用來做為巫術的器具。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Espejos hechos de obsidiana pulida, que es un vidrio oscuro y brillante formado en la naturaleza por el rápido enfriamiento de la lava. Tales espejos se usaron desde el Paleolítico. En la antigua Mesoamérica, como en otros lugares, fueron utilizados como instrumentos para ver.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000320/GRI-FloCo</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109721/GRI, FloCo terminology (2019-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Tezcatl tlachihualli ica ce tetl tlen quiillia obsidiana tlen tlahuel quialaxohtoqueh, nopa ce tezcatl zo tetl achi yayahuic huan pepetlaca tlen mochihchiuhtoc icelti ica nopa lava quemman nimantzin cehui. Nopa tezcatl motequihuihqueh ipan cahuitl Paleolitico. Ipan huahcapatl Mesoamerica, quence ipan cequinoc canahya, motequihuihqueh quence ce tlamantli para tlachiyazceh.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Eastern Huasteca Nahuatl</Note_Language>
